	<h1>Tuition and Fees Tax Deduction</h1>
	
	<p>Keep in mind that a tax deduction is different than a tax credit. Tax credits directly reduce the amount of your tax you owe.  A tax deduction reduces the amount of your income that the IRS may tax. The Tuition and Fees Tax Deduction is similar to deducting charitable contributions or mortgage interest to lower your taxable income.  The deduction can be used even if you do not itemize your taxes on a 1040 Schedule A.</p>
		
	<h3>Who Qualifies for this Deduction?</h3>
	
	<p>This deduction may only be taken by students at accredited colleges that are approved by the Department of Education.  In other words, if the school offers FFELP loans, it is an accredited college approved by the Department of Education.</p>	
	<p>A taxpayer can take the Tuition and Fees Deduction if the student is the taxpayer, taxpayer's spouse, or the taxpayer's dependent and if the student is enrolled at least on a 1/2 -time basis.</p>
	
